Here is a Basic Health Guide for Farmers â€” practical, easy-to-follow safety and health advice designed specifically for agricultural workers.

Farming involves exposure to chemicals, heat, heavy machinery, animals, and long working hours. Preventive care is extremely important.

ğŸšœ 1. Protection from Heat & Sun (Very Important in India)

Farmers often work long hours under direct sunlight.

â˜€ï¸ Heat Stroke Prevention

Drink water every 20â€“30 minutes (even if not thirsty)

Wear light-colored, loose cotton clothes

Use a wide hat or cloth to cover head

Avoid heavy work between 12 PM â€“ 3 PM

Take shade breaks

âš ï¸ Heat Stroke Symptoms

Dizziness

Headache

Vomiting

Confusion

High body temperature

ğŸ‘‰ If symptoms appear: Move to shade immediately, give ORS/water, and seek medical help.

ğŸŒ¾ 2. Safe Use of Pesticides & Chemicals

Pesticide exposure is one of the biggest health risks.

ğŸ§ª Safety Rules

Always wear gloves, mask, and full sleeves

Do NOT spray in strong wind

Do not eat or smoke during spraying

Bathe and change clothes after spraying

Store chemicals away from children

âš ï¸ Poisoning Symptoms

Breathing difficulty

Excessive sweating

Nausea

Blurred vision

ğŸ‘‰ In emergency: Go to nearest hospital immediately and carry pesticide container label.

ğŸšœ 3. Machinery Safety

Tractors, threshers, and harvesters cause serious injuries.

ğŸ›  Safety Tips

Do not wear loose clothes near machines

Switch off engine before repair

Keep children away from equipment

Never overload tractor

Use proper footwear

ğŸ„ 4. Animal-Related Safety

Livestock can transmit diseases.

ğŸ‚ Prevention

Wash hands after handling animals

Wear boots in animal sheds

Vaccinate animals regularly

Treat animal wounds immediately

Common risks:

Tetanus

Rabies (animal bites)

Skin infections

ğŸ¦Ÿ 5. Protection from Insects & Snakes

Fields may have mosquitoes, scorpions, and snakes.

Wear boots in fields

Use mosquito nets at night

Keep surroundings clean

Carry a torch at night

âš ï¸ Snakebite:

Stay calm

Do NOT cut or suck the wound

Go to hospital immediately

ğŸ« 6. Respiratory Health (Dust & Crop Residue)

Farm dust and smoke can cause lung disease.

Wear mask during harvesting/threshing

Avoid burning crop residue

Cover face in dusty areas

Symptoms of concern:

Long-term cough

Breathing difficulty

Chest tightness

ğŸ§  7. Mental Health of Farmers

Farming stress due to crop loss, debt, or weather is common.

Stress Management

Share problems with family

Join farmer groups or cooperatives

Take regular rest

Seek government support schemes

If severe anxiety, depression, or suicidal thoughts occur â†’ seek medical help immediately.

ğŸ’§ 8. Safe Drinking Water & Hygiene

Drink clean filtered or boiled water

Wash hands before eating

Keep nails trimmed

Use toilets (avoid open defecation)

ğŸ’‰ 9. Important Vaccinations for Farmers

Tetanus (every 10 years)

Rabies (if high animal exposure)

Hepatitis B

COVID-19

Influenza (optional but helpful)

ğŸ¥— 10. Nutrition for Farmers

Farm work requires high energy.

Eat:

Dal, milk, eggs (protein)

Green vegetables

Seasonal fruits

Jaggery for iron

Avoid excessive tobacco & alcohol

ğŸš¨ Emergency Numbers in India

Ambulance: 108

General Emergency: 112

Kisan Call Centre: 1800-180-1551

